body:
**Description**
Verilator fails to correctly handle variable declarations that are initialized with queue.size() when the declaration occurs inside a for loop within a task. The variable gets assigned incorrect values (0?) instead of the actual queue size.

Verilator Version: latest main
OS: Linux

cmd line for the snippted below: `verilator --binary --timing test_q.sv `

**Code to Reproduce**
```
module test_queue_size_bug;

    parameter DATA_WIDTH = 8;
    logic [DATA_WIDTH-1:0] expected_data_queue[$];

    task some_work();
        // Add 3 items to queue
        expected_data_queue.push_back(8'h01);
        expected_data_queue.push_back(8'h02);
        expected_data_queue.push_back(8'h03);

        // For loop with problematic queue size assignment
        for (int i = 0; i < 3; i++) begin
            //int queue_size_before = expected_data_queue.size();  // This line causes issues in Verilator
            int queue_size_before = 0; // This works
            queue_size_before = expected_data_queue.size();  // This works
            $display("i=%0d, queue_size_before=%0d, actual_size=%0d", 
                     i, queue_size_before, expected_data_queue.size());
        end
    endtask

    initial begin
        some_work();
        $finish;
    end

endmodule
```

**Test Case Output**

```
./obj_dir/Vtest_q 
i=0, queue_size_before=0, actual_size=3
i=1, queue_size_before=0, actual_size=3
i=2, queue_size_before=0, actual_size=3
```

